<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus greggii</i> is a low to rounded evergreen shrub with rigid branches that grows to 2 m in height. At 3 years, shrubs begin producing seed, which is explosively cast from plants as their capsules break. Most of the seed drops beneath the crowns of the shrubs. Seed predation by small mammals and insects may be severe, but with time, seeds collect in the duff and soil as a seed bank (Zouhar 2000a). <br/>
<br/>
Two of the four varieties of <i>Ceanothus greggii</i> are widespread in southern California (Hickman 1993). The more restricted var. <i>perplexans</i> grows in the San Bernardino Mountains and Peninsular Ranges; var. <i>vestitus</i> ranges from the Transverse Ranges east though the Tehachapi area along the desert margin of the southern Sierra Nevada and White Mountains to the Mojave Desert. Fross and Wilken (2006) and others have argued recently that the California plants are best treated as <i>C. perplexans</i> and <i>C. vestitus</i>. However, additional taxonomic analysis of plants referred to as <i>C. greggii</i> var. <i>vestitus</i> (or <i>C. vestitus</i>) and <i>C. pauciflorus</i> in the southwestern U.S. and Mexico are better combined into a single taxon with C. vestitus synonymized into <i>C. pauciflorus</i> (Burge and Zhukovsky 2013). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Fremontodendron californicum</i> is a medium to tall shrub to 3 (-5) m in height. After 2 years, shrubs begin producing seed, and they are prolific seed producers but germination may be variable. Plants also can resprout from a lignotuber following top-kill, and plants can grow rapidly after germination or resprouting (Pavek 1993b).<br/>
<br/>
Both <i>C. greggii</i> and <i>F. californicum</i> are components of desert chaparral vegetation that also inter-relate with desert scrub and pinyon-juniper woodland in post-burn settings. Many transmontane stands have been called desert, semi-desert, and transitional chaparral. Descriptions stress the open shrub canopy but differ in species composition. Some allow a significant tree component. The alliance definition builds on the original description of desert chaparral (Horton 1960), which lacks a common tree component. Stands are described at Long Canyon RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1990b).<br/>
<br/>
This alliance definition includes stands with <i>C. greggii</i> and <i>F. californicum</i> dominance (where <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> is 10% or less), stands with <i>C. greggii</i> and <i>A. fasciculatum</i> co-dominance, and stands with <i>C. greggii</i> and <i>F. californicum</i> co-dominance. The name and definition has been expanded since the publication of the 2009 A Manual of California Vegetation where it was cited as the <i>Ceanothus greggii</i> Alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
