<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Most stands of this alliance are associated with relatively recent fires. <i>Ceanothus greggii </i>may sprout weakly from stems or root crowns, but survival is generally low. As an obligate seeder, abundant seedlings are produced after fires, and germination between fires is negligible (Zouhar 2000a). Seeds germinate from the seed bank, and seedlings reach densities of 150/100 m2 (Keeler-Wolf 1990b). <i>Fremontodendron californicum </i>can either resprout from a lignotuber or can germinate from underground or off-site seed sources after fire (Pavek 1993b).

Post-fire stands attain dominance of <i>C. greggii </i> or <i>F. californicum </i>in as little as 4 years, when shrubs already average 30 cm in height and 50 cm in crown diameter. Older stands > 30 years tend to lose the dominance of these more early seral shrubs and include other species of sprouting shrubs (Keeler-Wolf 1990b, see Cheng 2004). Schmalbach et al. (2007) discussed the post-fire response of <i>Ceanothus </i>stands that were 12 years old and 60 years old in the Peninsular Ranges of San Diego Co. The older stands had significantly higher <i>C. greggii </i>regeneration than the younger ones.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
