    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cb). Stands occur along the westernmost fringe of the section (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh). A <i>Ceanothus greggii </i>stand has been sampled near Lake Crowley (Reyes et al. 2020a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ep, Er-s, Eu). Stands are found in the Piute, Scodie, and Tehachapi mountains, including Long Canyon RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1990b, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-d). Stands of <i>Fremontodendron californicum</i> have been sampled near Lake Isabella and near the town of Mariposa (CNPS field data 2008).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Ff). <i>Ceanothus greggii </i>stands have been sampled in the Panamint Range of Death Valley National Park (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb-d, Bg, Bi-j, Bl-p). Stands exist in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) and in the southern Peninsular Ranges (Evens and San 2005, Gordon and White 1994, Schmalbach et al. 2007). Four chaparral stands described by Gordon and White (1994) are placed here at this time.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The life history of <i>Ceanothus greggii</i> and <i>Fremontodendron californicum </i>suggest that canopy fires are needed for stand regeneration. Very long intervals between fires will reduce dominance of this type, while repeated short-interval fires may deplete the seed bank. </div>
</div>

    

    

